## Purpose

This document records how **{{COMPANY_NAME}}** approaches the topic above. It is the canonical reference for anyone — employees, contractors, investors, regulators — who needs to know what the company has committed to, and how.

Where the body of this document says *we* it means {{COMPANY_NAME}} as a legal entity. Where it says *you* it means the reader: employee, contractor, customer or partner.

## Scope

This document applies to every person who acts on behalf of {{COMPANY_NAME}} — directors, employees, contractors, advisors and third parties operating under our name. It applies regardless of location, role or seniority.

Exceptions to scope must be approved in writing by a director and recorded in the change log at the foot of this document.

## Who this is for

The primary audience is the team itself. The secondary audience is anyone who joins the company and needs to come up to speed quickly without reading the entire operating system from scratch.

If you are reading this as part of onboarding, read it through once end-to-end. If you are returning to it for reference, the section headings above are the navigation aid.

## Definitions

- **Director** — a person registered as a director at Companies House.
- **Officer** — a director, the company secretary, or any other person designated as an officer by the board.
- **Personnel** — employees and contractors with a current engagement.
- **Customer** — an organisation or individual that has accepted our terms of service and is using the product.
- **Confidential information** — anything labelled confidential, anything a reasonable person would treat as confidential, and anything covered by an NDA.

## Team responsibilities

Every member of the team is responsible for the integrity of their own work, for raising blockers early, and for keeping the operating system honest — that is, for flagging when a document drifts from how we actually operate.

No one is responsible for being right all the time. Everyone is responsible for being honest when they are wrong.

## Review and updates

This document is reviewed at least annually, and whenever a change to the business or to the law makes it obsolete. The review owner is recorded in the *Domain and Account Register*.

Material changes are signed off by the board and recorded in the change log at the foot of this document.

